(873, 'Games without Chance: Combinatorial Game Theory ', 'This course will cover the mathematical theory and analysis of simple games without chance moves.', 'ﾂ�This course explores the\nmathematical theory of two player games without chance moves. We will cover\nsimplifying games, determining when games are equivalent to numbers, and\nimpartial games. Many of the examples will be with simple games that may be new\nto you: Hackenbush, Nim, Push, Toads and Frogs, and others. While this probably\nwon窶冲 make you a better chess or go player, the course will give you a better\ninsight into the structure of games. \n\n\n\n', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/cgt', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=04-0W08GxTs', '2014-01-20', 7, 'https://d15cw65ipctsrr.cloudfront.net/23/520250f35e11e4a3446fae40268e71/Game-theory-icon-reshoot600x340.jpg', 'Math', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'Georgia Institute of Technology', '2015-11-21 09:19:36'),
(874, 'Feeding the World', 'Over the next 40 years, food production must double to meet the growing needs of the world population, which is estimated to exceed 9 billion by the year 2050. But, how do producers provide the growing human population with the needed food while maximizing the efficiency of production and minimizing impacts on the environment to ensure a sustainable future for us all?', 'This course will explore the concepts driving current food production science (population growth, urbanization, emerging affluence, resource constraints, and underlying biological limits) with the main focus on livestock production. Each of the major food animal species (dairy, swine, beef, and poultry) will be covered in terms of their universal life cycles, constraints to production and emerging societal issues.ﾂ� Throughout the course, we will tackle some difficult and important questions: What are the major health benefits and potential concerns regarding the production and consumption of animal products? How does animal production affect the efficient use of resources and impact our environment? Can cost of production be reduced to meet growing demand for animal products around the globe while maintaining health and safety for both animals and consumers? What are the different types of animal food production systems? Myths and misconceptions surrounding the animal food systems will be discussed. We窶冤l also look closely at some of the global issues, problems, and challenges in these food systems which scientists, farmers, and veterinarians, are attempting to solve through collaboration. Lectures will be delivered by several experts from the University of Pennsylvania, School of Veterinary Medicine who are intimately involved in the study and advancement of animal production systems. The course is geared towards learners who seek a greater understanding of animal food systems as well as those who might have never visited an animal farm, but have a desire to learn more about where some of our food comes from and issues surrounding sustainability.', 'https://www.coursera.org/course/feedingtheworld', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0571aeb02c8f11e5860d2b5a09fea2cd', '2021-01-01', 0, 'https://d15cw65ipctsrr.cloudfront.net/bc/c58b402c8a11e59bea1b8d7c95f5da/feeding-the-world-icon-FINAL-RESIZED-V4.jpg', 'Bio & Life Sci, Econ & Fin, Health, Nutrit', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'University of Pennsylvania', '2015-11-21 09:19:33'),
